# IntelliResearch — .cursorrules
# AI coding assistant rules for this project

## Project Context
This is a production-grade multi-agent AI research platform built with:
- Python 3.11+ with strict type hints everywhere
- FastAPI backend with async/await throughout
- LangGraph for agent orchestration
- Streamlit frontend
- Clerk authentication

## Code Quality Rules

### Always
- Add type hints to every function parameter and return type
- Write docstrings for every class and function (Google style)
- Use structured logging (never print statements)
- Handle every exception explicitly — never use bare `except:`
- Use pydantic models for all API request/response schemas
- Keep functions under 50 lines — split into helpers if longer
- Follow PEP 8 strictly (use ruff for linting)
- Use constants from config.py — never hardcode values
- Add inline comments for complex logic
- Use `@dataclass` or `TypedDict` for data structures

### Never
- Never commit API keys or secrets
- Never use `time.sleep()` in async code — use `asyncio.sleep()`
- Never ignore return values from async functions
- Never use `*` imports
- Never skip error handling in agent nodes
- Never use mutable default arguments

### Naming Conventions
- Classes: PascalCase
- Functions/variables: snake_case
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
- Private methods: _leading_underscore
- Type aliases: PascalCase with Type suffix

### Agent Node Rules
- Every agent node must return a dict with at least `events` key
- Emit progress events via `emit_event()` before and after processing
- Wrap all LLM calls in try/except with structured error return
- Log token usage on every LLM call

### Testing Rules
- Write a test for every agent node function
- Mock all external API calls in tests
- Use pytest fixtures for shared state
- Test both happy path and error cases

## File Organisation
- One class per file where possible
- Group related utilities in utils/
- Never put business logic in route handlers — use service layer
